snippet.textDisplay: As someone not necessarily "into" YouTube - who mostly uses it to watch stuff while doing chores and whatnot, never trying to branch out and can count the number of YouTube personalities they know on one hand (and most, if not all, of those are because of watching Game/Film Theory) - having never watched (and never would) a YouTube Rewind, I have to agree with MatPat's assessment of the obvious bias against the gamer creator community here. While I realize the games are what these creators play and there are obviously popular games for creators, it's often the creators who can bring popularity - or at least awareness/interest - to a game based on their viewership. So a list of top games on the platform might have made sense a few years ago, when it was the games themselves bringing in views for creators, popular creators are now the kingmakers. It's the very reason game developers - especially indie game developers - try to court the Let's Players and streamers to play their games and bring in business.
